commentText: When i planned to move and work in Germany i used a simplified version (enough to not be more than 2 pages in a pdf) of the EU standard. I avoided most unnecessary details.  However it depends on the position you are hunting for, if you speak German (very important) what experience you have already and the character of the company you are in. For example AG type of companies that focus on selling working hours as a source, focus a lot on how productive you are and how experienced you are and less in details not directive relative to that. Other positions focus in different things like languages, personality or other skills. In other words don't do a common mistake: make one template and send it to all. Personalise your CV to the position you want. And of course depending your industrial goals, you will always have companies easy to get you but also easy to fire you if you mess up badly in your testing period.

commentText: Just an addition to this process. If you have to get EU Blue Card then the German Embassy requires the diploma. If the diploma is not from EU universities then you need to go through Zeugnissbewertung from Sekretariat der Kulturministerumkonferenz hereinafter KMK in Bonn. The process costs 200 Euros and you have to pay the transaction fee.  For the KMK process you need to have the notarized copy of the diploma, then the notarized copy grades certificate, the simple copy of the high school - gymnasium and so on but for detailed list of documents needed you have to go to KMK Website and find out what is required for your documents from your country. I have got a job in Germany now waiting to obtain the visa. And the documents like grades transcript should be translated into German for KMK.
